---
layout: layouts/component-demo.njk
title: Five-Star Rating Picker
description: a picker for selecting a 1-5 star rating
---

{% from "components/five-star-rating-picker/macro.njk" import fiveStarRatingPicker %}
{% from "components/five-star-rating-picker-button/macro.njk" import fiveStarRatingPickerButton %}

<h2>How was your appointment?</h2>
{% call fiveStarRatingPicker({ label: "How was your appointment?" }) %}
  {{ fiveStarRatingPickerButton({ value: 5 }) }}
  {{ fiveStarRatingPickerButton({ value: 4 }) }}
  {{ fiveStarRatingPickerButton({ value: 3, checked: true }) }}
  {{ fiveStarRatingPickerButton({ value: 2 }) }}
  {{ fiveStarRatingPickerButton({ value: 1 }) }}
{% endcall %}

<h2>Service rating</h2>
{% call fiveStarRatingPicker({ label: "Rate the service" }) %}
  {{ fiveStarRatingPickerButton({ value: 5 }) }}
  {{ fiveStarRatingPickerButton({ value: 4 }) }}
  {{ fiveStarRatingPickerButton({ value: 3 }) }}
  {{ fiveStarRatingPickerButton({ value: 2 }) }}
  {{ fiveStarRatingPickerButton({ value: 1 }) }}
{% endcall %}

<h2>Layout note</h2>
<p>The example CSS renders the picker right-to-left so that the
  CSS sibling selector
  <code>.five-star-rating-picker-button:hover ~ .five-star-rating-picker-button</code>
  highlights <em>lower-valued</em> stars when you hover a higher
  one — a classic CSS-only star-rating pattern without JavaScript.</p>
